04658nam a22006135i 9780822384137DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223841377 a10.1515/97808223841372doi  a(DE-B1597)553998  a(OCoLC)1229161784  a(OCoLC)1167542031  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS3566.Y55bZ698 2002 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a813/.541 aMattessich, Stefan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLines of Flight :bDiscursive Time and Countercultural Desire in the Work of Thomas Pynchon /cStefan Mattessich; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (302 p.) :b4 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPost-Contemporary Interventions00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1 Imperium, Misogyny, and Postmodern Parody in V. -- t2 Ekphrasis, Escape, and Countercultural Desire in The Crying of Lot 49 -- t3 Turning Around the Origin in Gravity's Rainbow: Parody, Preterition, Paranoia, and Other Polymera -- t4 A Close Reading of Part 1, Episode 19, of Gravity's Rainbow -- t5 Docile Bodies and the Body without Organs: Gravity's Gravity's Rainbow -- t6 Totality and the Repetition of Di√erence: Rereading the 1960s in Vineland -- t7 A Vigilant Folly: Lines of Flight in Mason & Dixon -- tConclusion: Toward a Theory of the Counterculture -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor Thomas Pynchon, the characteristic features of late capitalism-the rise of the military-industrial complex, consumerism, bureaucratization and specialization in the workplace, standardization at all levels of social life, and the growing influence of the mass media-all point to a transformation in the way human beings experience time and duration. Focusing on Pynchon's novels as representative artifacts of the postwar period, Stefan Mattessich analyzes this temporal transformation in relation not only to Pynchon's work but also to its literary, cultural, and theoretical contexts.Mattessich theorizes a new kind of time-subjective displacement-dramatized in the parody, satire, and farce deployed through Pynchon's oeuvre. In particular, he is interested in showing how this sense of time relates to the counterculture of the 1960s and 1970s. Examining this movement as an instance of flight or escape and exposing the beliefs behind it, Mattessich argues that the counterculture's rejection of the dominant culture ultimately became an act of self-cancellation, a rebellion in which the counterculture found itself defined by the very order it sought to escape. He points to parallels in Pynchon's attempts to dramatize and enact a similar experience of time in the doubling-back, crisscrossing, and erasure of his writing. Mattessich lays out a theory of cultural production centered on the ethical necessity of grasping one's own susceptibility to discursive forms of determination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aCounterculturezUnited States. 0aDesire in literature. 0aEscape in literature. 0aTime in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384137zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384137423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822384137.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_AL